<% content_for :title, "Click-to-load — erbswap" %>

<h2>Example 3 &mdash; Click-to-load</h2>

<p class="example-intro">
  A list of articles. Click <em>Show preview</em> to fetch and swap a preview
  block in place. No form, no modal &mdash; just a click trigger via
  <code>data-erbswap-action="load"</code>.
</p>

<ul class="article-list">
  <% @articles.each do |article| %>
    <li class="article">
      <h3 class="article__title"><%= article[:title] %></h3>
      <p class="article__snippet"><%= article[:snippet] %></p>

      <div id="article-preview-<%= article[:id] %>" class="article__preview">
        <button type="button"
                class="button button--ghost"
                data-erbswap-action="load"
                data-erbswap-src="<%= examples_article_preview_path(article[:id]) %>"
                data-erbswap-target="article-preview-<%= article[:id] %>"
                data-erbswap-swap="replace">
          Show preview
        </button>
      </div>
    </li>
  <% end %>
</ul>

<details class="example-source">
  <summary>What's happening?</summary>
  <ol>
    <li>Each "Show preview" button has <code>data-erbswap-action="load"</code>. Clicking it triggers a <code>GET</code> to the article's preview URL.</li>
    <li>Each article has its own preview frame: <code>id="article-preview-1"</code>, <code>...-2</code>, <code>...-3</code>. Frames are scoped per item; the page can have many.</li>
    <li>The preview response wraps in the same id, so subsequent clicks would re-render in place. (Try refreshing to reset all of them at once.)</li>
    <li>This is the simplest trigger. No form, no submit handler &mdash; just a button as a hyperlink with a swap target.</li>
  </ol>
</details>
